London mr. Luey Kinghtley

& remitt you p dere frase, hopeing to finde a good marckett for the same, &
case they prove betder then the low puysed reds in the bale m. 10, which
bruly are butt cArdifferent. m. Collir is deu, & wee have minded yd. swalth

Brussel mr. Joseph Sabbarton
sence I wrott you on the 2t cour non from you, att which I do wender, laveing heav
that the compositonef Joan vale is not accepted, butt to the contraay, & ier
be in dn douse, & befled, pray lett iis know the certainitie of itt, aeilt
m. Collier is yett here. I hope to see you in the middle of neps week &
brugh mr Scawens bill, & yd sill dose with mee, Intrim con you remitt
mee mony, I hope to receavea good some, o pray give mee y advise by
times, for I inpose to come away a uerday or wedmes day

a 9 Jun
Mechelen juff. anna wigane
In Antw. aen din ul 5 deser bevinde de canten soo dier dat icq daer niet en
derf aencomen, sij sin voor mij niet, maer voor rinden van buyten, soo dat
de corrieten behonden naer advenant mijnen patroon te wesen, icq seynde ul
de canten wederom t bode, & hebbe de coriet allen uyt gehonden, waer van
geerne het alderminst soude weeten. hebbe geen ander van doen voor
aleen dat mijnen vert de saecke dese sal gesien hebben, oversulckx gelieft
den naesten prijs te adviseeren, ul beste daer voor te doen van andern
sorteerinige van canten hebbe scq geene van doen. ieq geloove dat m. van
then d'onde ƒ 200- aƒ 250- sal heblen getelt, soo niet gelieft hem sulckx te
vragen, alsoo hij diest aengenomen van over ½ sulck te doen
C 9 Junni 1682
Lille mr. Richard Soubhll
In answer to yd of 3 & 7th curtt. yd letter for mr. John wood have sent to Bruges, been
I have not mett hm, thougs se was here you need not to accomodate mee
with accepting my bill, for acctt of m follier, thougs I have already payd the
valew for hun with itt, because what you do upon that acctt. I will not
take to mij obleyd, if you will not accept itt, please to returne itt & first
a S'll take my measures accordingly, neither will I sufter, this to give you
cause to draw upon mee, where as mee thinckes, I am not vere forwaid
upon you, though I could wish I had in my sandes, what is yett with you
inposeinen to advance more by, the loss of time, & of e will bring the gaine to little
the more because I finde no acctt. from you of any new employ this yeare, se pray
lett mee know how all things stand for I love to please all my freinds, & you the
most which I iudge by a good musuall understanding is best maintained
m. Collier takes wagg on to marrow for Gant in order to see you att lille
lgen mr. wWill lobbe te Comny
a10 jun
I have recd. the last 2 bales you sent mee, the goods I finde vere ordinaind for their
sprijfes, a cours principally the cloth serges, so that I doubt they will not ender, what
I promised my self by the pattarnes, when fore lett mee intreat you to minde bouch
our intrest, & do do for mee, that Imight, contineu in with you longhes, so give mee
aminds in what now I iuorder by the inclosed note exspecting the ven best godds, for
such prijsen, as there by specified, for with the falling of the woole, & thenme, I quession
not, butt that the serges will be better & cleaper, & so pray provide these 4 bales to the
utmost of yd endeavour, that I might advance some thing by, when heu order the
goods as for pressing, foulding & packing as the last, & lett mee dave them by the
first vessel that comen for Bruges, which in case itt could not be, so lett mee have
att least ½ the parcell by the first, that is to say of every mentioned tort some thing
& then the rest by the next, if you can plaise mee, I will not questien butt you wile
finde itt worts yd while, lett mee have yd answer s first to god. my self
accordinglye
C 10 d.
London m. Abram Vivian
mj last to you wat on the ba cor. sende non from you, so this cleefley for covert to the
Inclosed invoyce of the packett n.7 for yd. ½ shae in which please to give mee
credit, beeng £58- flemish, as upon examinatiou I 2oye you nielfinde, fortr um god
send all safe to you, & a good marhett for them, this packett can not go away befoe
nept friday. I shall dispatch the rest of yd orders with all exped., I have bought
2 coandis of malime laces with 2 p for cust, most curious thinghs. I exspect
to jeare, hom you about goods ships in the north for if wee have not some
cloather, & white ware aboard the vere fust that gocts, itt would be preiudital
& whilst that smish tarries se long, I doubt not butt that itt will serve our
une, se pray endeavour all you can to advance our Intrest with you, as you may
be fune I'll do bere, &
a 10 f
London m. Pickeriug & Robbinsan
in some time sence swrott to you, which was for wat of ou in the meane while
I do the utmost of my endeavour to patt of our resting cloaches which now are yett
14 p & because bij lying they grow woise, am obliged to barter them for tykes, &
could with they would all go, I have shovre to m. Collies every p. & be will tell you
that be never save the like, so that I feare that acctt. will not under to epspectation
yett besure, I'll do my best, in the meane time if you please to dave bed tihes
in retournes, I'll send you a parell upon the vere best termes that can be
exspected
